s, then reversed themselves because of obstreperous behavior by Fidel Castro. The highly-charged negotiations with the Cuban leadership, who bitterly felt sold out by Soviet concessions to the United States, were led by Mikoyan. Adding personal crisis, Mikoyan's wife of more than 40 years died the day he arrived in Havana, yet he stayed to resolve the crisis through direct talks in Havana, New York, and Washington, amid constant communications with Moscow. The author, Sergo Mikoyan, who served as his father's personal secretary during these travels, vividly recalls how the Soviet relationship with revolutionary Cuba began and how it was shaped by the crisis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh1 aSavranskaya, Svetlana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSavranskaya, Svetlana, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107042040 cprintz978080476201440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362731440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503627314423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503627314/original  a978-3-11-070420-4  Stanford University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles